The [Artemis program](/Artemis_program), a truly ambitious undertaking led by the [United States](/United_States)' [National Aeronautics and Space Administration](/National_Aeronautics_and_Space_Administration) ([NASA](/NASA)), was formally etched into existence in 2017 through [Space Policy Directive 1](/Space_Policy_Directive_1). Its primary, and rather grand, intention is to reintroduce a human presence to the [Moon](/Moon) – a feat not accomplished since the distant days of [Apollo 17](/Apollo_17) in 1972. The long-term vision, as articulated, extends beyond mere footprints to the establishment of a [permanent base on the Moon](/Moonbase), a stepping stone, they claim, for eventual [human missions to Mars](/Human_mission_to_Mars). One can almost hear the cosmic sigh; another generation, another moonshot, another promise of Mars.

This latest endeavor borrows a few key components from its ill-fated predecessor, the [Constellation program](/Constellation_program). The bones of the [Orion spacecraft](/Orion_(spacecraft)) remain, albeit with a European [service module](/European_Service_Module) ([ESM](/European_Service_Module)) replacing the original U.S.-built design. Similarly, the powerful [Space Launch System](/Space_Launch_System)'s (SLS) [solid rocket boosters](/Space_Shuttle_Solid_Rocket_Booster) trace their lineage back to the [Ares V](/Ares_V) development. However, not everything is recycled. Novel elements, such as the orbital [Lunar Gateway space station](/Lunar_Gateway) and the [Human Landing System](/Human_Landing_System), are currently under development. This intricate web of creation involves a varied cast of characters: [government space agencies](/List_of_government_space_agencies) and the increasingly prevalent [private spaceflight](/Private_spaceflight) companies, all bound by the rather optimistically named [Artemis Accords](/Artemis_Accords) and a labyrinth of governmental contracts.

### Program Overview

The [Artemis program](/Artemis_program) is, at its core, a meticulously orchestrated series of deep-space missions, each building upon the last in a seemingly ever-increasing spiral of complexity. These missions are, of course, subject to the whims of budgets and engineering, thus scheduled to unfurl at intervals of a year or more, assuming no unexpected cosmic interventions or, more likely, budgetary squabbles. [NASA](/NASA) and its international partners have dutifully charted out missions from [Artemis I](/Artemis_I) through [Artemis V](/Artemis_V), with additional, more speculative missions proposed beyond that. Each of these core [SLS missions](/Space_Launch_System) is anchored by the launch of an [SLS launch vehicle](/Space_Launch_System), dutifully ferrying an [Orion spacecraft](/Orion_(spacecraft)) into the void. Anything beyond [Artemis II](/Artemis_II), however, demands a complex ballet of support missions, launched by a diverse array of organizations and spacecraft, performing all the necessary ancillary functions. It’s less a single journey, and more a meticulously choreographed traffic jam in space.

The trio of the [Space Launch System](/Space_Launch_System), the [Orion spacecraft](/Orion_(spacecraft)), and the [Human Landing System](/Human_Landing_System) constitute the primary [spaceflight](/Spaceflight) infrastructure for this grand lunar endeavor. The [Lunar Gateway](/Lunar_Gateway), a modular space station orbiting the Moon, plays a supporting role, offering a temporary home away from home. Beyond these central players, a constellation of supporting infrastructures includes the [Commercial Lunar Payload Services](/Commercial_Lunar_Payload_Services) (CLPS), the ongoing [development of ground infrastructures](/Exploration_Ground_Systems) back on Earth, the nascent [Artemis Base Camp](/Artemis_Base_Camp) on the Moon itself, a fleet of [Moon rovers](/Lunar_rover), and, naturally, the obligatory [spacesuits](/Space_suit). Unsurprisingly, given the scale and cost, certain aspects of the program have attracted a healthy dose of critique, from the choice of a [near-rectilinear halo orbit](/Near-rectilinear_halo_orbit) (NRHO) for the Gateway to the overall sustainability of the entire enterprise. One might say, the more things change, the more the critics remain the same.

The inaugural launch of [Orion](/Orion_(spacecraft)) atop the [Space Launch System](/Space_Launch_System) was initially penciled in for 2016. However, reality, as it often does, intervened with a series of rather predictable delays. It finally ascended on November 16, 2022, as the [Artemis I](/Artemis_I) mission, carrying a rather stoic cargo of robots and mannequins. As of November 2025 (and subject to the usual cosmic rescheduling), the crewed [Artemis II](/Artemis_II) mission is projected for an early 2026 launch. The actual human lunar landing, [Artemis III](/Artemis_III), is not expected to grace the lunar surface any earlier than mid-2027. Following this, [Artemis IV](/Artemis_IV) is slated for a late 2028 rendezvous with the [Lunar Gateway](/Lunar_Gateway). [Artemis V](/Artemis_V) is then planned for early 2030, bringing with it the [European Space Agency](/European_Space_Agency)'s [ESPRIT](/European_System_Providing_Refueling,_Infrastructure_and_Telecommunications) refueling and communications module, Canada's [Canadarm3](/Canadarm3) robotic arm, and [NASA](/NASA)'s own [Lunar Terrain Vehicle](/Lunar_Terrain_Vehicle). The [Artemis VI](/Artemis_VI) mission, which aims to integrate the [Crew and Science Airlock](/Crew_and_Science_Airlock_Module) with the [Lunar Gateway station](/Lunar_Gateway), is currently projected for early 2031. After this, [NASA](/NASA) optimistically envisions yearly landings on the [Moon](/Moon).

The program nearly met its demise in the early 2020s, a victim of the drastically shifting economics of launch, largely thanks to the advent of [reusable launch vehicles](/Reusable_launch_vehicle). After multiple congressional debates, the program, against all odds, secured its funding through the passage of the [2025 One Big Beautiful Bill Act](/One_Big_Beautiful_Bill_Act). A name that truly inspires confidence, doesn't it?

